Charlotte Folk has initiated a recall after customers raised issues about a misspelling on one of their products.
Over the weekend, several customers aired complaints about receiving a Redefining Sweater in Blue or Green that had a misspelled word. Instead of â€œredefining,â€ the sweater read â€œredifiningâ€.
Fans of BINI, who collaborated with Charlotte Folk for this drop, pointed out that even the sweaters Stacy and Jhoanna wore had the same misspelling.
The local streetwear brand quickly issued a statement that they will be â€œinitiating a recall for all Redefining Sweaters in Blue and Green due to a quality control oversight.â€
Customers who have received this faulty product can expect an email from Charlotte Folk. The brand also promised â€œcompensation options for the inconvenience caused.â€
â€œWe recognize that none of this is okay and we're truly sorry for the disappointment. We're fully committed to making this right and ensuring that your experience ends on a positive note. Thank you so much for understanding,â€ the statement ended.
Netizens praised the brand for quickly taking action. â€œKudos to team CF for admitting the lapse on their end and for taking action and doing this product recall. ğŸ‘ŒğŸ»,â€ an X (formerly Twitter) user wrote.
â€œI mean as they should di ba... pero in fairness naman talaga sa [Charlotte Folk], nakikinig sila sa customers nila,â€ another said.
Established in 2018 by Jan Charlotte Venzon, Charlotte Folk is a local streetwear brand specializing in cozy yet stylish pieces for the â€œurban muse.â€ The brand recently collaborated with the Nationâ€™s Girl Group BINI for its latest collection.

NASIRA ULO KO DITO: DBTK x H&M ğŸ¤¯
Nakakaproud maging parte ng PH Clothing Brand Community!
Malapit na talaga yung araw na hindi na peke o mababang klase kapag narinig ang salitang 'LOKAL' at nakakaproud dahil ang hiphop/streetwear scene sa bansa ang may pinakamatinding ambag dito.
Hiphop/streetwear scene na dating inaasar na pormahang mga dugyot daw. Pero makikita mo ngayon, maski Lola, Lolo, Nanay o Tatay ay may mga nagsusuot na ng local brands.
Malayo na ang narating pero malayo pa talaga, sabi nga ni Sir Douglas Brocklehurst, halos 2% pa lang ang nagsusuot ng local brands sa bansa. Malaki pa ang misyon! Malaki pa ang pangarap!
At darating yung araw na mawawala na yung salitang #SupportLocalBrand na para bang nagmamakaawa dahil lahat bilang isang bansa, proud na proud tayo sa mga locally-produced merch!
Tindihan pa natin ang kalidad! Magkakaroon din ng mga Pinoy Brand na tatangkilikin ng buong mundo! Sigurado ako dun!
Padayon, Filipino Clothing Brand Community!
Salamat sa inspirasyon, Don't Blame the Kids Apparel Co.!

"Iâ€™m collaborating with our good friends over at Instinct Studios to produce a tee to let you wear your love for toy collection and fashion on your sleeve!
Instinct Studios has been around since 2019. This unapologetic brand is young, but they've changed the local streetwear scene for the better. It believes in the potential of local artists to use textile and fabric as a vessel to express themselves. The Instinct Studios team has been dedicated to putting the work of local artists and designers in the forefront by producing high-quality apparel with one goal in mind â€” to make you look too good to be ignored! 
Instinct Studios have worked with different names and brands such as NOBRVND, Pawssion Project, and more. Each partnership has been instilled with advocacy while never compromising their steadfast brand of style.
I've always wanted to work with the people from Instinct Studios as I am a fan of streetwear/designwear, myself. Not to mention, one of my missions as a multifaceted artist is to dabble in apparel design, too. This collab is a creative outlet for us to maximize what we can do and broaden our perspectives as artists.
Projects like this help us foster our next career milestones to life and, most importantly, share our love of toys with a growing community. It's a means for us to escape the isolation of the global pandemic that we're living through right now. Plus, it's another way for us to meet like-minded individuals who share the excitement that I have for artisanship. 
That's why I'm thrilled to work with them as a fellow creative agent that's also obsessed with all things artistic. They're also sponsoring me at Art Toys PH's MADBOX 30: Online Custom Show, a custom art toy show on June 24 to 30, 2021, at Solid Toys Greenhills. It's an event that strengthens the toy community through socializing and shining the spotlight on great toy designers. International and local toy lovers absolutely can't miss it. BTW, this is also one of the things that helped make this collaboration happen.
I've always admired similar collaborations from big brands like Supreme x Medicom Toy or maybe even KAWS x Uniqlo x Sesame Street. Not to get all #PEENOISE PRIDE, but the Filipino market deserves an accessible toy and streetwear collaboration that they can truly call their own. That's why it's important for us to bring this collaboration to the local hypebeast scene. 
And besides? What better way to express your love for toys and fashion than wearing a flashy shirt that'll turn heads! 
Show exclusive tee available at https://instinct.ph/collect.../artcade-jl-x-instinct-studios & at the show venue for 895PHP. " -Artcade JL

Founded in 2019, @calleconph was initially an effort to unite the local urban community who found their passions in local hiphop and street style. It was a roaring success as the first Calle Con gathered 32 live acts and 54 local brands to successfully intersect the two pillars of street culture.
And in 2022, after a three-year hiatus due to the pandemic, Calle Con came back stronger as a two-day festival with 50 of the best live artists in the game, 80 local streetwear brands present, 10 streetwear fashion shows, a skate tournament, and a dance battle. With Filipinos ready to connect through music and style once again, we expect a bigger and better Calle Con this 2023.

Park Seo Joon is the newest celebrity to join the roster of ambassadors of a popular local clothing brand in the Philippines.

BATIK FABRIC IS NOT FILIPINO.  Though proliferating in Philippine cultural shops and even used as a brand by sellers who advocate Filipino textilesâ€¦ please know that Batik (as a fabric and as a dyeing technique) is Indonesian and Malaysian. It is a traditional craft that is also handed down in Singapore, India, Bangladesh and Sri Lanka.
It is NOT Filipino.
Batik (like other textiles) can be used IN Filipiniana style clothes (like to make butterfly sleeves), but the textile is not ours.
The ancient art of making Batik (wax-resist dyeing) originated in  Java, Indonesia.  Batik is a dyeing technique that uses resin and fabric dye to create patterns and designs. 
Central Javanese designs are influenced by traditional patterns and colors. Batik from the north coast of Java is influenced by Chinese culture, bearing bright colors and more intricate flower and cloud designs.
This art found modern renditions in Malaysia  where most popular motifs are leaves, flowers and geometrical designs with colors that are  lighter and more vibrant than Javanese batik.
The batik pieces for sale in Mindanao are imported from those countries, often arriving by boat from nieghboring islands.
To say that batik is Filipino is uninformed and is cultural misappropriation.
#hapihabi #hapihabiph #knowyourphilippines #knowyourculture #learn #educateyourself #philippines #culturalmisappropriation #beinformed

Since 2016, @purveyrfair has been a local gathering rooted on retail pop-ups that features many different creative communities. And through these communities and their distinct expressions we have continuously experienced an undeniable inspiring energy in the past eight fairs. It has been a beautiful intersection of commerce, culture and creativity.
PURVEYR Fair is an amalgamation of different cultures, inspirations, aesthetics, and ideas â€” from street artists, streetwear brands, fashion labels, homeware concepts, tattoo shops, barber collectives, and more. This diversity in ideologies is the main motivation for this yearâ€™s PURVEYR Fair visuals.
To express this idea, the @PURVEYR team worked with designer Kristian Henson (@kristian_henson) to create this yearâ€™s @purveyrfair identity â€” a concoction of many different elements that represent our teamâ€™s belief on diversity and its role in keeping the fair vibrant, creative, and inspiring.
Today, we formally launch the tickets to #PURVEYRFair2023 for guests who would love to join us in this two-day gathering on September 2-3, 2023 happening at Metrotent Convention Center, Pasig City. You can visit the link on our bio for the ticket link or by going straight to purveyr.helixpay.ph

LOOK: Macbeth staged a successful fashion show incorporating live band while its models were on the catwalk for three sets of collections.
The fashion show was half of the concert-and-fashion theme of #MacbethMusicFest: The 20th Anniversary Show of the popular clothing brand.
This was in line with their passion for music, the arts, and denim. The latest of Macbeth's Collection was featured alongside the official launch of Lady Macbeth and Macbeth Underwear.
As for the concert part, 20 band lineup were carefully selected across various genres within the main and underground music community. From noon to late night, attendees basked in the sounds and atmosphere of the performances by Chelsea Alley, Urbandub, Rico Blanco, Mayonnaise, Chocolate Factory, Sandwich, Hilera, Even, Snakefight, Sucketseven, Fragments, Chndtr, Fastpitch, Soapdish, Written By The Stars, Divina, Lilith, Shotgun Combo, Imbue No Kudos, Rouge, and Macbeth All-Stars and Superband.
Happy 10 years, Macbeth in the Philippines. And happy 20 rocking years of Macbeth in the world!

Will Dylan Wang come to the Philippines as he is now an endorser of a popular clothing brand?
Dylan Wang, who plays Dao Ming Si in the latest adaptation of Taiwanese classic Meteor Garden, is the newest face of a popular clothing brand here in the Philippines. 
â€œSo yeah. This happened. Wish grantedâ€”[Dylan Wang] is officially on our squad,â€ confirmed Bench on Instagram today, December 2, much to the delight of his Filipino fans.
t was in late November when the local clothing brand, who has since gone international, hinted at having Dylan as their newest global ambassador. Not surprisingly, this also led fans to eventually speculate that the Chinese actor is soon to visit the Philippines.
However, they have yet to confirm if rumors of his visit are indeed true.
Aside from Dylan, Korean actors Park Hyung Sik and Lee Min Ho, as well as American star Dylan Sprouse, were also previously named as part of the roster of their global ambassadors.

BENCH
Bench started in 1987 as a small t-shirt shop in SM Makati, founded by Ben Chan. At that time, most Filipinos dressed conservatively, but Bench introduced casual and stylish clothing. The brand quickly became popular and expanded into jeans, underwear, accessories, and even fragrances.
Over the years, Bench grew beyond fashion. It opened Bench CafÃ©s, Bench Fix Salons, and Bench Skin Expert clinics. It also brought international brands like Cotton On and Under Armour to the Philippines.
Did you know? Ben Chan comes from a family of entrepreneursâ€”his parents founded Liwayway Gawgaw, a well-known starch brand in the Philippines.
Today, Bench has over 600 stores in the Philippines and branches in the U.S., Middle East, and China. It has worked with global stars like Bruno Mars, Brooklyn Beckham, and Lee Min Ho. The brand also supports young designers through the Bench Design Awards.
Benchâ€™s success is closely tied to SM, where it got its first big break. Ben Chan believes that starting small doesnâ€™t mean staying small. Bench is proof that a Filipino brand can grow into a global name, inspiring others to dream big and push boundaries in fashion and beyond.

LIWAYWAY GAWGAW
Liwayway Gawgaw is a brand deeply tied to Filipino history and daily life. It started in 1948 when Chinese-Filipino couple Chan Lib and See Ying saw an opportunity in cornstarch. They repackaged it into smaller, affordable packs and sold them in sari-sari stores. The name â€œLiwayway,â€ meaning â€œdawn,â€ reflected the optimism of a newly independent Philippines.
For decades, Liwayway Gawgaw was a household essential. It kept clothes crisp and fresh, perfect for baroâ€™t saya, Americana suits, and school uniforms. In the 1960s, a popular radio jingle cemented its place in Filipino culture.
Did you know? Liwaywayâ€™s packaging has remained unchanged since 1946, making it one of the countryâ€™s most nostalgic products.
Over time, the brand expanded beyond cornstarch. In 1974, it introduced Oishi snacks, which became a massive success in the Philippines and China. The foundersâ€™ son, Ben Chan, later launched Bench, a global fashion brand. Despite this growth, Liwayway Gawgaw remains on store shelves, a tribute to its humble beginnings.
More than just a product, Liwayway Gawgaw represents resilience, tradition, and Filipino ingenuity. It is a reminder of a time when simple things, like a box of starch, held an important place in every home.

LIWAYWAY GAWGAW
Liwayway Gawgaw is a brand deeply tied to Filipino history and daily life. It started in 1948 when Chinese-Filipino couple Chan Lib and See Ying saw an opportunity in cornstarch. They repackaged it into smaller, affordable packs and sold them in sari-sari stores. The name â€œLiwayway,â€ meaning â€œdawn,â€ reflected the optimism of a newly independent Philippines.
For decades, Liwayway Gawgaw was a household essential. It kept clothes crisp and fresh, perfect for baroâ€™t saya, Americana suits, and school uniforms. In the 1960s, a popular radio jingle cemented its place in Filipino culture.
Did you know? Liwaywayâ€™s packaging has remained unchanged since 1946, making it one of the countryâ€™s most nostalgic products.
Over time, the brand expanded beyond cornstarch. In 1974, it introduced Oishi snacks, which became a massive success in the Philippines and China. The foundersâ€™ son, Ben Chan, later launched Bench, a global fashion brand. Despite this growth, Liwayway Gawgaw remains on store shelves, a tribute to its humble beginnings.
More than just a product, Liwayway Gawgaw represents resilience, tradition, and Filipino ingenuity. It is a reminder of a time when simple things, like a box of starch, held an important place in every home.

HANG TEN
In 1960, a young surfer named Duke Boyd had an idea. What if there were shorts made just for surfing? He teamed up with Doris Boeck, who sewed the first boardshorts. To make them special, they added a small embroidered logo of two feet. That simple design became the start of something big.
At first, the brand was only popular among surfers in California. But as the years passed, it expanded beyond surfwear. By the 1970s, Hang Ten was selling t-shirts, hoodies, and everyday clothes. The brand reached many countries, including the Philippines in the 1980s. Many Filipinos remember shopping for Hang Ten shirts in malls like SM and Robinsons.
Did you know? In the 80s and early 2000s, Hang Ten was one of the most popular brands for students and young adults.
As time went on, more fashion brands entered the market. Hang Ten struggled to keep up. By the late 2000s, its stores in the Philippines started closing. While it still exists in other countries, for many, it remains a nostalgic memory of beach trips, casual weekends, and comfortable clothes that lasted for years.

Today, with a continuous stream of projects, a new business, and a fully-constructed family home, Blythe finally finds herself in a place where she can occasionally treat herself to luxury itemsâ€”even her dream bag. Press play to discover the exact designer pieces that have brought joy to Blythe, with no regrets or second thoughts.
